# readme.yawn

A tiny open file system for seeing the frame you are inside.

## tl;dr

`.yawn` is a plain-text file format for shared mental models.

It helps a human or agent pause, see the current frame, name what is missing,
choose one bounded move, protect agency, gather proof, and replay what changed.

The whole system is this:

```text
see the frame
name the lacuna
choose a bounded move
gather proof
replay what changed
```

That is YAWN.

## abstraction-1

Your brain already has an interface. It is attention, memory, emotion, belief,
habit, body signal, relationship, constraint, and action.

The problem is that a human mind is bad at holding many moving parts at once.
Five things is already a lot. Add an AI agent, a project, a relationship, a
deadline, a memory, and a body signal, and the frame gets noisy.

`.yawn` gives that inner interface somewhere simple to land.

## what are we doing?

We are building the simplest possible open-source interface for agency.

Not another dashboard. Not another productivity system. Not another chatbot.
Not another game.

A `.yawn` is a small readable object that lets a human and an AI agent share the
same frame without pretending the agent is the authority.

The root file is called `readme.yawn` because this README is not only explaining
the project. It is the first YAWN object.

The public GitHub home is:

```text
https://github.com/yawn-ai/.yawn
```

The repo is MIT licensed. The copyright holder is The Yawn Company.

## how to use yawn

YAWN is a mirror.

You use it by organizing your life, projects, relationships, records, and next
moves into `.yawn` files.

Each `.yawn` is like a madlibs frame:

```text
i am observing ___
the current frame is ___
the possible frame is ___
what is missing is ___
the smallest safe move is ___
the boundary is ___
proof would look like ___
afterward, what changed was ___
```

You can fill it out alone, with another person, or with any AI. The AI can help
mirror, organize, ask clearer questions, find proof gaps, and suggest smaller
moves.

The point is not to outsource your selfhood.

The point is to interface better with yourself.

Start with:

```text
start/how-to-use-yawn.yawn
templates/basic.yawn
```

## feedback

Feedback should be easy.

If something is confusing, useful, missing, too abstract, too intense, or
surprisingly helpful, send it to:

```text
yawn@yawn.ai
```

The feedback node lives in:

```text
feedback/node.yawn
feedback/form.yawn
feedback/email-intake.yawn
feedback/codex-t4o-parser.yawn
records/feedback-log.yawn
database/feedback-intake.yawn
```

The near-term form is intentionally simple: it opens an email to
`yawn@yawn.ai`. The intake contract says that feedback email should be logged,
parsed by Codex/T4O, classified, and written to the correct database location.

Public feedback form:

```text
https://yawn-ai.github.io/.yawn/feedback/
```

## the leading question

The leading question is:

```text
how does a human move from implicit pattern to explicit agency?
```

Everything in this repository exists to help answer that question.

A `.yawn` should help someone see:

```text
what is here?
what is shaping it?
what is missing?
what can i safely try?
what would prove movement?
what changed?
```

## what are we observing?

We are observing lived agency: the way a human or agent sees a frame, carries a
model, chooses a move, meets reality, records proof, and updates memory.

The named observation node is:

```text
observations/lived-agency.yawn
```

That file states the actual object of observation. It keeps the system from
drifting into "everything." We are not observing the source code of the
universe. We are observing the current interface between a person, a situation,
tools, constraints, other agents, and proof.

## why a file tree?

Because the file tree is the first interface.

A folder can show:

```text
this is the frame
this is where it lives
this is what it depends on
this is unresolved
this is proof-backed
this can move next
```

The app can come later. The graph can come later. The game world can come
later. The agent cockpit can come later.

The root is:

```text
one folder
one readme.yawn
many readable .yawn files
```

## folders are nodes

Every folder is a knowledge node and a mental-model node.

That means a folder is not only a place where files are stored. It is a named
part of the shared model. It should tell a human or agent what kind of thinking
lives there, what it receives, what it produces, and what question it helps
answer.

Each folder has a local `node.yawn` file.

Open `node.yawn` first when entering a folder. It is the folder's orientation
card.

The folder-node protocol lives in:

```text
core/folder-node.yawn
```

## five-command brain interface

The public entry point is five cognition handles:

```text
/mirror
/map
/meaning
/move
/memory
```

These are not terminal commands yet. They are handles a person can remember.

`/mirror` shows what is happening now. See `interface/mirror.yawn`.

`/map` shows what this belongs to. See `interface/map.yawn`.

`/meaning` names the gap between current and possible. See
`interface/meaning.yawn`.

`/move` chooses the smallest authorized step. See `interface/move.yawn`.

`/memory` records proof and replays what changed. See `interface/memory.yawn`.

## core ontology, gently

YAWN has a deeper ontology, but nobody should need to learn it all at once.

Start here:

```text
mirror
map
meaning
move
memory
```

Then the deeper terms become easier:

```text
frame
signal
lacuna
axis
agency
boundary
proof
replay
handoff
record
```

The ontology is linked out rather than stuffed into one wall of text:

```text
start/what-is-a-yawn.yawn
core/movement-frame.yawn
core/lacuna.yawn
core/agency.yawn
core/proof-and-boundary.yawn
core/observer-and-body.yawn
interface/projection-stack.yawn
records/material-time.yawn
references/scientific-frame.yawn
```

## duality

The core duality is:

```text
observer <-> embodied human
```

The observer can step back and notice patterns.

The embodied human needs stability, food, sleep, money, safety, relationship,
nervous-system regulation, and ordinary reality.

YAWN is not about escaping the body. It is about seeing the pattern without
abandoning the human.

The lock:

```text
notice the pattern without becoming the pattern
inhabit the body without being trapped by inherited identity
imagine a possible frame without forcing it as truth
choose a bounded move without abandoning stability
use proof without crushing mystery
```

## what a .yawn file is

A `.yawn` file is a movement frame.

It can be loose prose, YAML-ish structure, or a mix. It should be readable by a
human first and mappable by an agent second.

The rule:

```text
human-readable first
machine-addressable second
proof-bound when promoted
```

A minimal `.yawn` looks like this:

```yaml
title: "a thing i am observing"

current: "what is happening now"
possible: "what could become possible"
lacuna: "what is missing, unknown, blocked, or not yet bridged"

move: "the smallest authorized next relation or action"
boundary: "what must not be forced or assumed"
proof: "what would show that something actually changed"
replay: "what changed after observing or moving"
```

Use `templates/basic.yawn` for the smallest shape. Use `templates/full.yawn`
when the frame needs axes, agent boundaries, proof state, and replay fields.

## projection stack

A `.yawn` observes the user's current interface with reality.

Not the source code of the universe.

The source code of this frame.

That means:

```text
beliefs are code
habits are code
language is code
body signals are code
relationships are code
constraints are code
artifacts are code
proof receipts are code
agent packets are code
```

They are "code" because they shape what appears possible.

## proof and boundary

YAWN must not become a certainty machine.

The safety rail:

```text
signal != instruction
resonance != proof
coincidence != command
memory != objective record
ai output != authority
intensity != truth
only proof updates the map
```

Everything can be observed. Some things can be interpreted. Fewer things should
be acted on. Only proof updates the map.

## material records

`.yawn` also records material time.

That means files, tool use, LLM-used context, GitHub access, backups, commits,
external surfaces, decisions, costs, proof receipts, and next-move logic.

Records live in:

```text
records/material-time.yawn
records/access-log.yawn
records/llm-access.yawn
records/github-access.yawn
records/backup-log.yawn
records/next-move-ledger.yawn
```

This keeps the system from becoming only interpretation. If an agent used a
file, a command, a GitHub surface, or a backup to decide the next move, the
record layer should be able to say so.

## agents

A `.yawn` is also an agent handoff packet.

It tells an AI agent:

```text
what the human sees
what the frame is
what is missing
what move is invited
what proof matters
what boundary blocks hidden authority
```

An agent may mirror, clarify, map, summarize, question, propose, find proof
gaps, surface conflicts, prepare bounded next steps, and record material
accesses.

An agent must not silently decide truth, rewrite identity, force action, mutate
source files, publish externally, spend resources, hide uncertainty, or turn
resonance into proof.

Human authority stays visible.

The named repo service role is:

```text
yawn.bot
```

Today, `yawn.bot` runs as a daily Codex automation:

```text
agents/yawn.bot.yawn
automation/yawn.bot.daily.yawn
automation/yawn.bot.feedback-loop.yawn
records/yawn.bot-log.yawn
```

It can inspect, classify, and recommend. It can help prepare a contribution.
It does not secretly become a GitHub account, install an app, commit, push,
comment, merge, send email, or write a database without current human
authorization.

The feedback-to-commit gate is:

```text
feedback -> node -> thesis -> risk review -> proof -> bounded change -> commit readiness
```

Enough feedback is not only volume. It means a pattern can be stated as a
clear thesis, the risks and dissent are visible, proof is named, and the
authority state is explicit.

## open-source agent contributors

This repo should be easy for humans and AI-assisted contributors to improve.

The contribution path lives in:

```text
contributing.md
.github/ISSUE_TEMPLATE/ai-agent-contributor.yml
agents/contributor-agent.yawn
agents/contributor-architecture.yawn
agents/yawn.bot.yawn
automation/github-feedback-triage.yawn
automation/yawn.bot.daily.yawn
```

If someone has an AI workflow that can help YAWN, they should be able to show:

```text
what mission the agent helps with
what architecture it uses
what files or surfaces it reads
what it can write or propose
what proof keeps it honest
what human approval it needs
```

The durable automation identity should be clear. Use a GitHub App or dedicated
bot/service account later, not a hidden personal account.

## altruistic frame

The larger hope is shared orientation.

People, teams, governments, institutions, and AI systems often fail because
they do not share the same frame. They argue from hidden assumptions, mismatched
values, different proof standards, and incompatible maps of what is happening.

`.yawn` gives people a way to say:

```text
here is my current frame
here is the possible world i am pointing toward
here is what i think is missing
here is what i am not allowed to assume
here is what would count as proof
here is what changed after we moved
```

Not forcing agreement.

Making disagreement legible.

That is the altruistic bet.

## detailed updated plan

1. Make `readme.yawn` the canonical root orientation file.

2. Keep `readme.md` as a small compatibility pointer for platforms that expect
   Markdown.

3. Name the object of observation in `observations/lived-agency.yawn`.

4. Teach the ontology through five cognition handles in `interface/`.

5. Keep templates small enough that a person can create a first yawn without
   learning the whole system.

6. Preserve the research basis in `references/` and `08-research/`.

7. Use `records/` for material time: LLM access, GitHub access, backups, proof,
   and next-move logic.

8. Give every folder a `node.yawn` so folders are explicit knowledge nodes and
   mental-model nodes.

9. Keep the GitHub repo public at `https://github.com/yawn-ai/.yawn`, under the
   MIT License, with The Yawn Company as copyright holder.

10. Add a feedback path that sends email to `yawn@yawn.ai`, logs feedback as a
    record, and defines how Codex/T4O should parse it into the database.

11. Add GitHub-native contribution surfaces for feedback, PRs, and AI-agent
    contributor architectures.

12. Run the `yawn-repo-feedback-triage` automation hourly to inspect repo
    feedback and contributor signals without changing external state.

13. Run the `yawn-bot-daily-repo-contributor` automation daily as the named
   `yawn.bot` service loop for repo contribution recommendations.

14. Use `automation/yawn.bot.feedback-loop.yawn` to decide when feedback is
   strong enough to become a thesis, a risk-reviewed move, and eventually a
   commit-ready contribution.

15. Treat apps, graphs, games, and agents as later surfaces over the file tree,
   not the root.

## first proof strip

The first product proof is one complete loop:

```text
create a yawn
seed the frame
see the axis map
choose a bounded move
gather proof
replay what changed
```

Everything else is secondary until that loop works.

## first move

Create one file:

```text
first-yawn.yawn
```

Write:

```yaml
title: "my first yawn"

current: "something has my attention"
possible: "i can see it more clearly"
lacuna: "i do not yet know what is missing"

move: "pause and name the signal"
boundary: "do not force an answer"
proof: "i can name one clearer question"
replay: "what changed after naming it?"
```

That is enough.

## final lock

`.yawn` is the file format for structured movement through lived reality.

It is how a human or agent can say:

```text
i am observing this
this is the frame
this is the missing bridge
this is the bounded move
this is the proof
this is what changed
```

That is what we are doing.
